om":"Faversham, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Patrixbourne, Bridge, Kent, England":"Patrixbourne, Kent, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Beach","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: topographic name from Middle English <i>beche</i> ‘beech-tree’ (Old English <i>bēce</i>) or Middle English <i>beche</i> ‘stream’ (Old English <i>bæce</i>). Middle English <i>beche</i> may be from Old English <i>bēce</i> ‘beech’ or <i>bæce</i> ‘stream’, and without further evidence it is impossible to distinguish these in Middle English.","Americanized form of Alsatian and German <b>Bitsch</b>: habitational name from Bitche (German <i>Bitsch</i>) in Alsace and Lorraine, at the foot of the northern slope of the Vosges.","Americanized form of German (mainly Hesse) <b>Bitsch</b>: unexplained."],"variants":[{"name":"Beech","meanings":["English: variant of   Beach  .","Americanized form of German or Alsatian <b>Bitsch</b> (see   Beach  ) or of some other similar (like-sounding) surname."]},{"name":"Beecher","meanings":["English (Kent): from Middle English <i>becher</i>, denoting one who lived by a beech-tree, from an agent derivative of Middle English <i>beche</i> ‘beech-tree’ (see   Beach  ), the <i>-er</i> suffix having a locative sense. This English name is also common in Ireland, particularly in Cork.","Americanized form of German <b>Bücher</b> (cognate with 1 above) (see   Bucher  )."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Robert Beach was born in 1576, in Faversham, Kent, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 daughter with Robert Beach. She died in her hometown."},"et":{"1576–":"1576–Surnud","1572–1620":"1572–1620","1620–1664":"1620–1664","1576–Female":"1576–Surnud","1576":"1576","1620":"1620","1664":"1664","1572":"1572","Faversham, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Faversham, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Patrixbourne, Bridge, Kent, England":"Patrixbourne, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1576–":"1576–Kuollut","1572–1620":"1572–1620","1620–1664":"1620–1664","1576–Female":"1576–Kuollut","1576":"1576","1620":"1620","1664":"1664","1572":"1572","Faversham, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Faversham, Kent, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Patrixbourne, Bridge, Kent, England":"Patrixbourne, Kent, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1576–":"1576–Décédée","1572–1620":"1572–1620","1620–1664":"1620–1664","1576–Female":"1576–Décédée","1576":"1576","1620":"1620","1664":"1664","1572":"1572","Faversham, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Faversham, Kent, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Patrixbourne, Bridge, Kent, England":"Patrixbourne, Kent, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Mrs. Robert Beach est née en 1576, à Faversham, Kent, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Elle a eu au moins 1 fille avec Robert Beach. Elle est décédée dans sa ville natale."},"de":{"1576–":"1576–Verstorben","1572–1620":"1572–1620","1620–1664":"1620–1664","1576–Female":"1576–Verstorben","1576":"1576","1620":"16